<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="697" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[811,1457,1236,1645]" box="[813,1086,1236,1262]" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">PRELIMINARY STATEMENT</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[811,1457,1236,1645]" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">
Turtles are well represented in Angeac-Charente, notably by numerous isolated shell plates and bones of the axial and appendicular skeletons, and more rarely by articulated shell material (see 
<tableCitation box="[953,1033,1363,1389]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="53.[132,143,219,236]" captionTargetId="graphics-134@53.[132,1455,565,2024]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="TABLE 1. — List of vertebrate taxa from the Jurassic-Cretaceous transition of Charente with their relative abundances in each locality, habitat, stratigraphic range and Mesozoic geographical distribution.The black, grey and white squares represent the preferred habitats of each taxon. Abbreviations: A, abundant; C, common; CZ, costal zone; FW, freshwater; J, Middle Jurassic; LC, Lower Cretaceous; LJ, Lower Jurassic; LP, Lower Permian; LT, littoral; MT, Middle Triassic; NA, North America; PR, paralic; R, rare; SA, South America; TR, terrestrial; UC, Upper Cretaceous; UCa, Upper Carboniferous; UJ, Upper Jurassic; UP, Upper Permian; UT, Upper Triassic." pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Table 1</tableCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[1047,1145,1363,1390]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="52.[132,143,1815,1832]" captionTargetBox="[94,1455,198,1785]" captionTargetId="figure-60@52.[94,1455,198,1785]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="FIG. 35. — A, Relative abundance of Angeac-Charente large vertebrate taxa based on identified macroremains collected from 2010 to 2017. White numbers indicate the Minimum Number of Individuals (MNI) (after Rozada et al. 2021); B, Relative abundance of Angeac-Charente taxa, based on microremains collected in 2017, by water screen-washing (diameter of mesh = 0.8 mm), at the base of the unit 3, of the R3 plot." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902120" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902120/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Fig. 35A</figureCitation>
). Only a few pieces of skulls, including a maxillary and a mandible, have been recovered. 
<bibRefCitation author="Neraudeau" box="[813,1060,1427,1454]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Neraudeau" pageId="16" pageNumber="697" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref44595" refString="NERAUDEAU D., ALLAIN R., BALLEVRE M., BATTEN D. J., BUFFE- TAUT E., COLIN J. P., DABARD M. P., DAVIERO- GOMEZ V., EL ALBANI A., GOMEZ B., GROSHENY D., LE LoeUFF J., LEPRINCE A., MARTIN- CLOSAS C., MASURE E., MAZIN J. - M., PHILIPPE M., POUECH J., TONG H., TOURNEPICHE J. - F. &amp; VULLO R. 2012. - The Hauterivian-Barremian lignitic bone bed of Angeac (Charente, SW France): stratigraphical, palaeobiological and palaeogeographical implications. Cretaceous Research 37: 1 - 14. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2012.01.006" type="journal article" year="2012">
Néraudeau 
<emphasis box="[934,983,1427,1453]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">et al.</emphasis>
(2012)
</bibRefCitation>
have previously reported the presence of three distinct turtle taxa in Angeac-Charente: a pleurosternid, a solemydid (now helochelydrid), and a third taxon characterized by shell bones without surface ornamentation (
<figureCitation box="[821,895,1554,1581]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="18.[132,143,1940,1957]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-29@18.[698,1267,768,1324]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIG. 12. — Helochelydrid and thalassochelydian turtle remains from Angeac-Charente: A, peripheral plate of Helochelydridae indet. in dorsal view;B, pleural plate of Helochelydridae indet. in dorsal view; C, D, right hyoplastron of Hylaeochelys belli? (Mantell, 1844) (ANG18-5915) in ventral (C) and dorsal (D) views; E, left humerus of Hylaeochelys? belli? (ANG18-5937) in ventral view; F, right humerus (ANG18-5938) in dorsal view;; G, H, Peripheral of Hylaeochelys? belli? (ANG 18-5993) in dorsal (G) and ventral (H) views. Scale bar: A, 1 cm; E-H, 2 cm; B, 3 cm; C, D, 4 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902061/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">Figs 12</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[907,934,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="20.[132,143,1146,1163]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1102]" captionTargetId="figure-346@20.[132,1455,215,1102]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIG. 13. — Pleurosternid turtle from the Berriasian of Angeac-Charente: A, carapace of Pleurosternon bullockii (Owen, 1842) (ANG14 R-454) in dorsal view; B, plastron and right peripheral plates 1 and 2 of Pleurosternon bullockii (ANG14 R-474 &amp; ANG15 R-1082) in ventral view. Scale bar: 10 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6902063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6902063/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="697">13</figureCitation>
). Since then, additional and more complete material confirms these preliminary conclusions (see below). The third taxon is now identified as a thalassochelydian.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
